{% highlight bash html %} ln -s [TARGET DIRECTORY OR FILE] ./[SHORTCUT] {% endhighlight %}
For example
{% highlight bash html %} ln -s /usr/local/apache/logs ./logs {% endhighlight %}
This points a symbolic link &ldquo;./logs&rdquo; to &ldquo;/usr/local/apache/logs&rdquo;

With four lines, you&rsquo;ll be able to type the beginning of the command (e.g. &ldquo;cd&rdquo;) and press the up arrow to see the most recent command containing the text you typed (e.g &ldquo;cd ~/Library&rdquo;).
{{ more }}
This makes it much easier to find what you&rsquo;re looking for. To make this happen, create a text file called .inputrc in your home folder and put the following four lines inside:
{% highlight bash html linenos %} &ldquo;\e[A&rdquo;: history-search-backward &ldquo;\e[B&rdquo;: history-search-forward set show-all-if-ambiguous on set completion-ignore-case on {% endhighlight %}
